È±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±¼

þ Calculator

þ Built-in assembler! Press <tab> in CodeMode.

þ Recording and playback of macros.

þ Built-in disassembler! Check out CodeMode inside HexIt ( <F4> is the
  default key for choosing mode ).

þ 80x25/28/43/50/60 textmode hexeditor. HexIt starts up in the videomode
  you used when starting the program if it is one of the above, else it
  uses 80x25. This is of course fully configurable, you can choose to
  start in e.g 80x50 if you want to. But then again, you're always in
  80x50 anyway, aren't you? The win32 version can startup with any
  number of lines as long as it's not more than 140.

þ Supports 100 files in memory at the same time.

þ Files may be as big as your total amount of free memory. Virtual
  memory can be used in the win32 version.

þ SplitScreen facilities.

þ Editing. Yes! =)

þ Preserves your "pre-HexIt" videomode, and initializes your favourite
  80x12 textmode (or whatever you use) upon exit if you so desire...

þ Deleting bytes and thereby shrinking the file.

þ Inserting bytes and thereby expanding the file. You can also set the
  Insert/Overwrite toggle to Insert, and then type whatever you like,
  HexIt will push the rest of the file forward for you.

þ Clipboard (maximum size equals your free mem minus the total size of
  your loaded files) with cut, copy and paste!

þ Goto fileoffset, both absolute and relative.

þ Hex/ASCII search- and replace-facilities. Forwards/Backwards, all
  files/one file, etc.

þ Online help.

þ Ability to view files as a normal textviewer would.

þ This entire file is loaded and displayed if you press Alt+H.
  Functionkeys are always explained at the bottomrow.

þ Create new files simply by giving their name as an argument.

þ Compare two files. Read more about it further down.

þ A setup mode where you can alter colours, configure keys etc.

þ Mousesupport! Scroll the screen using your mouse. Define what HexIt
  will do when a specific mouse-button is pressed!

þ Supports wildcards when loading files, thus
  "HexIt gunde.* gnu ka??.txt" is perfectly valid.

þ EXE-header info.


